<br>
<p>
Note that theoretically, it is always possible to 'downgrade' the measureme=
nt level of a variable. For instance, a test that can be performed on a var=
iable of ordinal measurement level can also be performed on a variable of i=
nterval measurement level, in which case  the interval variable is downgrad=
ed to an ordinal variable. However, downgrading the measurement level of va=
riables is generally a bad idea since it means you are throwing away import=
ant information in your data (an exception is the downgrade from ratio to i=
nterval level, which is generally irrelevant in data analysis).
</p>
<p>
If you are not sure which method you should use, you might like the assista=
nce of our <a href=3D"https://statkat.com/statistical-technique-selection/t=
ool-for-selecting-a-statistical-technique.php" target=3D"_self">method sele=
ction tool</a> or our <a href=3D"https://statkat.com/stattest_overview.php"=
 target=3D"_self">method selection table</a>.
</p>



